question:
Indicate which of the following is a linear combination of $A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      3& 2\\
			0 & 1 
    \end{array}\right]$, $B=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      0& -1 \\
			1 & 2 
    \end{array}\right]$ and $C=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      5& 4 \\
			-1 & 0
    \end{array}\right]$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \\ 
1 & 0 & 3 \\ 
0 & -1 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & 0 \\ 
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
-1 & 1 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$. Find $\mathrm{det} \left(X\right)$ knowing that $$\frac{1}{2} X\cdot A +  \mathrm{det} \left(B\right) \cdot A=B$$
